On coming back from Prague to Berlin, I found Lydia in the kitchen engaged in beating an egg in a glass—“goggle-moggle,” we called it. “Throaty aches,” she said in a childish voice; then put down the glass upon the edge of the stove, wiped her yellow lips with the back of her wrist and proceeded to kiss my hand. She had on 